# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: bill-craver
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:bill-craver/1871-in-baseball] The tenth founding member, the National club of Washington, did not enter a team for the championship until 1872.
[src:bill-craver/1872-in-baseball] The following are the baseball events of the year 1872 throughout the world.
[src:bill-craver/1873-in-baseball] The following are the baseball events of the year 1873 throughout the world.
[src:bill-craver/1874-in-baseball] The following are the baseball events of the year 1874 throughout the world.
[src:bill-craver/1875-in-baseball] The following are the baseball events of the year 1875 throughout the world.
[src:bill-craver/1876-in-baseball] The following are the baseball events of the year 1876 throughout the world.
[src:bill-craver/1876-in-baseball] After a tumultuous five-year existence, the National Association of Professional Base Ball Players (NA) folded following the 1875 season.
[src:bill-craver/1876-in-baseball] One of the new rules put into place by the new league was that all teams had to be located in cities that had a population of 75,000 or more.
[src:bill-craver/1876-in-baseball] The initial NL season began with eight teams, and they were asked to play seventy games between April 22 and October 21.
[src:bill-craver/1876-in-baseball] The NL is often considered to be the first "major league", although it has been argued that the NA can make that claim.
[src:bill-craver/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] The **1877 Louisville Grays scandal** was an incident in which members of the Louisville Grays baseball team accepted money to lose games.
[src:bill-craver/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] Four players – Bill Craver, Jim Devlin, George Hall and Al Nichols – were subsequently banned from professional baseball for life.
[src:bill-craver/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] In the early days of professional baseball, crooked play was not uncommon, and many players were suspected of throwing games in exchange for money.
[src:bill-craver/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] Illegal influence by gamblers had undermined the National Association of Professional Base Ball Players (NA) in the early 1870s, and William Hulbert formed the National League (NL) in 1876 with the intention of driving it out of the game.
[src:bill-craver/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] Nevertheless, there were still several gambling-related scandals during the 1876 season.
[src:bill-craver/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] Jim Devlin started his baseball career in 1873 and was the Louisville Grays' pitcher in 1876 and 1877.
[src:bill-craver/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] In 1876 he had a win–loss record of 30–35 and an earned run average of 1.56, while leading the league in complete games, innings pitched and strikeouts.
[src:bill-craver/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] In 1877, Devlin went 35–25 with a 2.25 ERA and again led the league in complete games and innings pitched.
[src:bill-craver/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] He started and completed each of the Grays' 61 games, an accomplishment no other pitcher in history has matched.
[src:bill-craver/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] Outfielder George Hall was one of the best sluggers in the game's early history.
[src:bill-craver/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] After playing in the NA from 1871 to 1875, he joined the Philadelphia Athletics in 1876.
[src:bill-craver/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] That season, he led the league with five home runs and finished second in batting average, on-base percentage, slugging percentage and total bases.
[src:bill-craver/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] In 1877, he played for the Grays and had a .323 batting average.
[src:bill-craver/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] Shortstop Bill Craver was a noted crooked player who had been expelled from a previous team for throwing games in 1870.
[src:bill-craver/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] He played for the New York Mutuals in 1876 before joining the Grays the following season.
[src:bill-craver/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] Al Nichols also played for the Mutuals in 1876.
[src:bill-craver/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] He joined the Grays in the middle of the 1877 season on the recommendation of Hall and appeared in six games for the team.
[src:bill-craver/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] Newspapers named the players "Terror" Devlin, "Gentleman George" Hall, "Butcher" Craver and "Slippery Elm" Nichols".
[src:bill-craver/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] After the games of August 13, 1877, the Grays were in first place by four games over St.
[src:bill-craver/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] Louis and 4.5 over the Boston Red Caps, with a record of 27 wins and 13 losses, and with some 20 games left to play.
[src:bill-craver/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] They then commenced a nine-game winless streak (including one tie) and eventually lost the championship to Boston.
[src:bill-craver/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] They won six out of their last seven, making their season record of 35-25 look reasonably respectable, but those wins came after Boston had clinched the pennant, having won 20 of their final 21 games.
[src:bill-craver/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] Louisville finished second, seven games behind Boston.
[src:bill-craver/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] Chase received telegrams informing him of suspicious gambling activity involving the team.
[src:bill-craver/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] He started an investigation, and Devlin and Hall confessed to throwing several exhibition games late in the season, with Devlin receiving up to $100 per game.
[src:bill-craver/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] On October 4, the entire team was gathered, and Chase demanded that they turn over their telegrams.
[src:bill-craver/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] Every player except Craver complied, and the telegrams showed that Devlin, Hall and Nichols had thrown games.
[src:bill-craver/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] On October 30, Craver, Devlin, Hall and Nichols were expelled from the club, and on December 4, the NL banned them from professional baseball for the rest of their lives.
[src:bill-craver/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] The Grays franchise folded after the 1877 season.
[src:bill-craver/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] Over the next few decades, there were fewer suspicions of game-fixing in professional baseball.
[src:bill-craver/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] The four banned players were never reinstated.
[src:bill-craver/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] Nichols played semi-professional baseball, Craver and Devlin became police officers, and Hall worked as an engraver and clerk.
[src:bill-craver/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] Devlin tried to be reinstated many times but was unsuccessful.
[src:bill-craver/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] In one instance, he got on his knees and begged Hulbert for another chance.
[src:bill-craver/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] Hulbert responded by handing him $50 (roughly equivalent to $1,200 in 2017 value) and saying, "Devlin, that's what I think of you personally; but, damn you, you have sold a game; you are dishonest and this National League will not stand for it." Devlin died of tuberculosis in 1883.
[src:bill-craver/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] His 1.90 career ERA is the third-lowest of all-time among pitchers with at least 1,000 innings pitched.
[src:bill-craver/bill-craver] Before his baseball career, Craver had served in the military during the Civil War with the 13th Heavy Artillery Regiment out of New York.
[src:bill-craver/bill-craver] He enlisted on January 21, 1864, as a Private in Company K, and mustered out on June 28 in Norfolk, Virginia.
[src:bill-craver/bill-craver] When the war, and his military career were over, he began his organized baseball career as a catcher in 1866 with the Union Baseball Club of Rensselaer County, which became the Unions of Lansingburgh.
[src:bill-craver/bill-craver] The Unions gained the nickname of Haymakers in August of that year after a visit to the Capitoline Grounds and the Elysian Fields.
[src:bill-craver/bill-craver] Later, in 1870, while playing for a Chicago team, he was accused of breaking his contract with the team.
[src:bill-craver/bill-craver] In 1871, Craver joined the Troy Haymakers, who entered the National Association of Professional Base Ball Players in the league's first season.
[src:bill-craver/bill-craver] He played second base, and after just four games, he replaced Lip Pike as manager.
[src:bill-craver/bill-craver] He played well, batting .322, but the team finished in seventh place.
[src:bill-craver/bill-craver] For the next two seasons, he joined the Baltimore Canaries, the first of which he was player-manager.
[src:bill-craver/bill-craver] He was replaced at manager later in the year by Everett Mills, but stayed with the team through the 1873 season.
[src:bill-craver/bill-craver] Playing for the Philadelphia White Stockings in 1874, he led the league in games played, and as a second baseman, he led the league in putouts and errors.
[src:bill-craver/bill-craver] Craver had his best offensive season that year, batting .343 and leading the league in stolen bases.
[src:bill-craver/bill-craver] In 1875, he moved over the Philadelphia Centennials.
[src:bill-craver/bill-craver] He played in just 13 games for them when, together with George Bechtel, he was traded to the Philadelphia Athletics to replace injured players Dave Eggler and Wes Fisler in exchange for $1,500.
[src:bill-craver/bill-craver] He led the NA in triples in 1875 with 13.
[src:bill-craver/bill-craver] The National Association folded following the 1875 season, and Craver joined the 1876 New York Mutuals, a team that he also managed.
[src:bill-craver/bill-craver] It was his only season in New York, as the Mutuals were expelled from the league for not making the required western trip.
[src:bill-craver/bill-craver] It was during this season that Craver was reputedly savagely beaten by a gambler for doublecrossing him on a fix.
[src:bill-craver/bill-craver] He gained infamy the following season, his final season, when playing for the Louisville Grays.
[src:bill-craver/bill-craver] In 1877, the Grays were ahead in the league standings, with a 27–13 record with only 15 games left to play, but then lost their lead through horrible play, losing eight straight games at one point.
[src:bill-craver/bill-craver] The trouble reportedly began when third baseman Bill Hague was injured and needed to be replaced.
[src:bill-craver/bill-craver] George Hall suggested that the team pick up his former Mutuals teammate Al Nichols.
[src:bill-craver/bill-craver] The errors by Nichols, Hall, and Craver began to accumulate, and owner Charles Chase became suspicious when he noticed that Nichols was still in the lineup, even though Hague was fully healthy.
[src:bill-craver/bill-craver] The players were soon seen around town with new clothes and jewelry.
[src:bill-craver/bill-craver] Chase confronted pitcher Jim Devlin and did not receive a confession, but Hall thought Devlin had confessed.
[src:bill-craver/bill-craver] Hall claimed that Nichols was the person in contact with the gamblers and all three had thrown games.
[src:bill-craver/bill-craver] Chase requested from each member of the team permission to see all the Western Union telegrams sent and received.
[src:bill-craver/bill-craver] Craver was the only man on the team to refuse, which caused him to be suspended.
[src:bill-craver/bill-craver] The telegrams proved the three were in open communication with the gamblers.
[src:bill-craver/bill-craver] After his forced retirement from baseball, Craver became a police officer, along with fellow "criminal" Devlin.
[src:bill-craver/bill-craver] He began to receive military disability on July 1, 1892, as a result of time as a soldier, which would continue on to his widow, Catherine C.
[src:bill-craver/bill-craver] Craver died at the age of 57 of heart disease in his hometown of Troy, and is interred at Oakwood Cemetery.
